{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "For the past few years, researchers have been holding forums to see how people would ration limited medical resources during disasters or pandemics....", "abstract": "Researchers in Maryland, in effort to shape public health care policy, have been asking American citizens for their opinions on rationing and allocating medical resources in large-scale emergencies like disasters or epidemics;  effort is among the first times that a state has gathered informed public opinion on such questions before devising policy on them, and hope is that outcome can help shape national model. ", "section_name": "U.S.", "print_page": "9", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Sheri", "role": "reported", "lastname": "FINK", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By SHERI FINK", "contributor": ""}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/22/us/whose-lives-should-be-saved-to-help-shape-policy-researchers-in-maryland-ask-the-public.html", "lead_paragraph": "For the past few years, researchers have been holding forums to see how people would ration limited medical resources during disasters or pandemics.", "headline": {"main": "Whose Lives Should Be Saved? Researchers Ask the Public", "print_headline": "Whose Lives Should Be Saved? To Help Shape Policy, Researchers Ask the Public"}, "_id": "57ba5d7b95d0e021d7981e26", "word_count": "1360", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/08/22/us/22triage4/22triage4-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/08/22/us/22triage4/22triage4-thumbWide-v2.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 422, "url": "images/2016/08/22/us/22triage4/22triage4-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/08/22/us/22triage4/22triage4-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "422"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2016/08/22/us/22tr